Christian Zionism is a rather specific, some might say peculiar, [political and religious ideology](/Political_and_religious_ideology) that exists within a broader [Christian context](/Christianity_and_Judaism). Its central tenet is the fervent belief in the return of the [Jewish people](/Jews) to the ancestral [Holy Land](/Holy_Land). This isn't merely a historical or humanitarian aspiration; for Christian Zionists, the [founding of Israel](/Founding_of_Israel) in 1948 wasn't just a geopolitical event, but a direct, undeniable fulfillment of [biblical prophecies](/Bible_prophecy) meticulously laid out in the [Old Testament](/Old_Testament). They contend that the re-establishment of [Jewish sovereignty in the Levant](/History_of_the_Jews_and_Judaism_in_the_Land_of_Israel)—often termed the eschatological "[Gathering of Israel](/Gathering_of_Israel)"—is an absolute prerequisite for the grand finale, the [Second Coming of Jesus Christ](/Second_Coming). The phrase "Christian Zionism" itself, a relatively modern construct, only gained traction in the mid-20th century. Before that, it was often referred to as [Christian restorationism](/Restorationism_(disambiguation)), but the shift occurred as proponents actively aligned themselves with [Zionists](/Zionism) in advocating for a [Jewish national homeland](/Homeland_for_the_Jewish_people).

One might assume this support is altruistic, a simple act of solidarity. But, of course, nothing is ever simple. The expectation of Jewish restoration among Christians isn't some fleeting modern fad; its roots stretch back to 17th-century English [Puritan](/Puritan) thought, where the initial sparks of Christian pro-Zionist ideals first flickered. Indeed, contemporary Israeli historian [Anita Shapira](/Anita_Shapira) rather pointedly suggests that England's Zionist [Evangelical Protestants](/Evangelicalism) were so enthusiastic they "passed this notion on to Jewish circles" around the 1840s. One can only imagine the conversation.

However, here’s where the narrative takes a turn that might raise a few eyebrows, especially among those being "supported." While vociferously advocating for a mass Jewish return to the [Land of Israel](/Land_of_Israel), Christian Zionism simultaneously champions a rather inconvenient parallel idea: that these returnees should be actively encouraged, if not outright pressured, to [reject Judaism and adopt Christianity](/Conversion_of_the_Jews_(future_event)). Because, naturally, their return isn't truly complete until they conform to a different set of [biblical prophecies](/Bible_prophecy). It’s a subtle distinction, perhaps, but one that has not gone unnoticed. Polling data and academic research have consistently revealed a widespread, and frankly unsurprising, distrust among Jews regarding the true motivations of [Evangelical Protestants](/Evangelicalism). These groups, after all, are simultaneously promoting robust support for the [State of Israel](/State_of_Israel) while actively [evangelizing the Jews](/Proselytization_and_counter-proselytization_of_Jews). It's almost as if they see a divine transaction rather than genuine partnership.

### History before the 20th century

