#### Origins in Calvinistic millennialism

•
Main articles: [History of the Puritans](/History_of_the_Puritans), [Millennialism](/Millennialism), and [Christian Zionism in England and Scotland](/Christian_Zionism_in_England_and_Scotland)

It’s often said that history repeats itself, but sometimes it just recycles old ideas with a fresh coat of paint. Take [Thomas Brightman](/Thomas_Brightman), an English Puritan, for instance. In 1615, he published "Shall They Return to Jerusalem Again?", a title that leaves little to the imagination. This was one of the earliest, if not *the* earliest, explicit [Restorationist](/Restoration_Movement) works of its kind, laying groundwork that would prove surprisingly resilient.

Initially, the prominent Protestant leaders of the Reformation, figures like [Martin Luther](/Martin_Luther) and [John Calvin](/John_Calvin), didn't exactly have "Jewish return to Palestine" high on their eschatological agenda. Their [eschatological](/Christian_eschatology) views were, shall we say, less geographically specific. Luther, ever the optimist, had initially hoped that Jews would flock to his particular brand of Christianity once he had decisively broken ties with the [Catholic Church](/Catholic_Church). When that didn't quite pan out, he pivoted to rather [harshly denouncing Jews](/On_the_Jews_and_Their_Lies). A classic move. Both the [Lutheran Church](/Lutheranism) and the [Reformed Church](/Calvinism), mirroring the older [Catholic Church](/Catholic_Church) and [Eastern Orthodox Church](/Eastern_Orthodox_Church), comfortably viewed the Christian Church as the "spiritual Israel." Faithful Christians were the exclusive "[people of God](/People_of_God)," the true inheritors of the covenant through [Jesus Christ](/Jesus_Christ), thus neatly assigning no special privileges or future role to individuals of Jewish descent. This theological framework, which effectively replaced the literal Israel with the Christian Church, would later be rather delicately termed [supersessionism](/Supersessionism).

However, the Protestant emphasis on *[sola scriptura](/Sola_scriptura)*—scripture alone—and the burgeoning availability of the [Bible](/Bible) in vernacular languages across Europe, inadvertently opened a Pandora's Box of interpretations. Various [radical Protestants](/Radical_Reformation) began to pore over the scriptures, drawing their own conclusions, often diverging wildly from both established medieval [Catholic tradition](/Catholic_tradition) and the views of the very [Magisterial Protestant](/Magisterial_Protestant) leaders who had set them on this path. This exegetical freedom coincided with a broader cultural phenomenon: a general [Hebraizing](/Hebraism) trend among these more radical Protestant factions. Rejecting the [veneration of saints](/Calendar_of_saints) as outright [idolatry](/Idolatry), they instead fixated on the [biblical patriarchs](/Patriarchs_(Bible)) and [prophets](/Prophets_of_Christianity) of the [Old Testament](/Old_Testament). It became fashionable, almost a statement, to name children Abraham, Cain (yes, Cain), Jeremiah, Zachary, Daniel, Sampson, and other such distinctly Old Testament monikers.

The notion of Jews returning to [Palestine](/Palestine_(region)) to reclaim it as their national homeland first gained significant traction among self-identified Christian groups in the 1580s. These were predominantly aligned with [Puritanism](/Puritanism), a particularly rigorous Reformed branch of Christianity that eventually spawned the [Congregationalist](/Congregationalist) denomination. It started subtly enough. During the reign of [Edward VI of England](/Edward_VI_of_England), a child-monarch, a Calvinist-leaning Regency effectively governed [England](/England). This opportune moment allowed influential Continental Protestants like [Martin Bucer](/Martin_Bucer) and [Peter Martyr Vermigli](/Peter_Martyr_Vermigli) to teach at the venerable universities of Cambridge and Oxford. These two intellectual heavyweights advanced a [biblical exegesis](/Biblical_exegesis) that, notably, carved out an important, if rather conditional, role for Jews—specifically, converted Jews—in the unfolding [end times](/Eschatology). Early versions of the Bible sanctioned by the English monarchy and the [Anglican Church](/Anglican_Church), such as the [Great Bible](/Great_Bible) and the [Bishops' Bible](/Bishops%27_Bible), were seen by many English [Puritans](/Puritans) and [Lowland Scots](/Scottish_people) [Presbyterians](/Presbyterians) as far too "Romanist" in their leanings, along with Episcopalianism and the established "[Protestantism of the princes](/Magisterial_Reformation)." In response, a number of these Puritans and Presbyterians decamped to [Geneva](/Geneva) in the 1560s, placing themselves under the tutelage of Calvin's successor, [Theodore Beza](/Theodore_Beza). There, they meticulously developed their own translation, the [Geneva Bible](/Geneva_Bible). This edition, critically, included footnotes to the [Book of Romans](/Book_of_Romans) that explicitly asserted the future conversion of the Jews to Christianity in the end times, thereby reorienting eschatological attention to Palestine as a central stage for these divine dramas. This perspective was enthusiastically adopted by a formidable roster of English Puritans, including [Francis Kett](/Francis_Kett), [Edmund Bunny](/Edmund_Bunny), [Thomas Draxe](/Thomas_Draxe), [Thomas Brightman](/Thomas_Brightman), [Joseph Mede](/Joseph_Mede), [William Perkins](/William_Perkins_(theologian)), [Richard Sibbes](/Richard_Sibbes), [Thomas Goodwin](/Thomas_Goodwin), [William Strong](/William_Strong_(priest,_died_1654)), [William Bridge](/William_Bridge), [Henry Finch](/Henry_Finch_(died_1625)), [John Owen](/John_Owen_(theologian)), and [Giles Fletcher]. It also found fertile ground among Lowland Scots Presbyterians such as [George Gillespie](/George_Gillespie), [Robert Baillie](/Robert_Baillie), and [Samuel Rutherford]. Even some Continental Protestants, including [Oliger Paulli](/Oliger_Paulli), [Isaac Vossius](/Isaac_Vossius), [Hugo Grotius](/Hugo_Grotius), [Gerhard Vossius](/Gerhard_Vossius), and [David Blondel], were swayed by these theories.

The Puritans, initially a "fringe" faction, found themselves in an unexpected position of power under [Oliver Cromwell](/Oliver_Cromwell) during the Commonwealth. It's almost amusing how quickly fringe ideas can become state policy when the right people seize control. Several of Cromwell's closest advisors were, rather conveniently, adherents of Philo-Semitic millennialist religious views.

During the late Tudor and early Stuart periods, these Puritans remained marginalized outsiders in England, fiercely opposing the [Laudian](/Laudian)-dominated Anglican Church. Meanwhile, their Presbyterian counterparts, holding very similar theological convictions, had managed to establish the [Church of Scotland](/Church_of_Scotland) as the dominant "[Kirk](/Kirk_(word))" in Scotland. The [English Civil War](/English_Civil_War) proved to be their moment, as Puritans swelled the ranks of the [Parliamentarians](/Roundheads) and the formidable [New Model Army](/New_Model_Army). Under the decisive leadership of [Oliver Cromwell](/Oliver_Cromwell), they emerged victorious, executing [Charles I of England](/Charles_I_of_England) and consolidating complete state power, which ushered in the [Commonwealth of England](/Commonwealth_of_England) between 1649 and 1660. This shift in power allowed the deeply ingrained [Philo-Semitic](/Philo-Semitic) [millennialist](/Millennialist) undercurrent to directly influence state policy. A number of Cromwell's trusted advisors, including [John Dury](/John_Dury), [John Sadler](/John_Sadler_(Town_Clerk_of_London)), and [Hugh Peter](/Hugh_Peter), actively engaged with [Dutch-based Jews](/History_of_the_Jews_in_the_Netherlands) like [Menasseh ben Israel](/Menasseh_ben_Israel). They passionately advocated for [Jewish resettlement in England](/Resettlement_of_the_Jews_in_England), a remarkable turnaround given that Jews had been formally banned from the country since the 13th century. Sadler, who served as Cromwell's secretary, even went so far as to argue in his pamphlet *The Rights of the Kingdom* (1649) that the British were, in fact, one of the [Lost Tribes of Israel](/Lost_Tribes_of_Israel), thereby establishing a kinship with the Jews and inadvertently initiating the controversial movement of [British Israelism](/British_Israelism). Other Puritans, such as [Jeremiah Burroughs](/Jeremiah_Burroughs), [Peter Bulkley](/Peter_Bulkley), [John Fenwicke](/John_Fenwicke), and [John Cotton](/John_Cotton_(minister))—some of whom had migrated to the [Massachusetts Bay Colony](/Massachusetts_Bay_Colony)—saw Jewish re-entry into England as a crucial step towards their ultimate return to Palestine. This entire sequence of events was meticulously woven into a grand millennialist eschatology, designed to hasten the [Second Coming](/Second_Coming) of Jesus Christ and, consequently, the [final judgement](/Final_judgement). Johanna and Ebenezer Cartwright, two Baptists who had spent time in [Amsterdam](/Amsterdam), shared this fervent view and were instrumental in submitting the original petition to [Thomas Fairfax](/Thomas_Fairfax)'s Council of War in January 1649, advocating for Jewish readmission. Their petition optimistically declared, "That this Nation of England, with the inhabitants of the Netherlands, shall be the first and the readiest to transport Israel's sons and daughters on their ships to the land promised to their forefathers, Abraham, Isaac, and Jacob for an everlasting inheritance." By 1655–1656, a de facto toleration for Jews in England was informally established, a policy that, surprisingly, was not reversed even after [the Restoration](/Stuart_Restoration).

A notable French-born figure, [Isaac La Peyrère](/Isaac_La_Peyr%C3%A8re), though nominally a [Huguenot](/Huguenot) Calvinist, hailed from a Portuguese [New Christian](/New_Christian) family (converted [Sephardic Jewish](/Sephardic_Jewish)). He emerged as a significant 17th-century progenitor of these ideas, wielding influence on both sides of the [English Channel](/English_Channel). In his millennialist work *Du rappel des juifs* (1643), La Peyrère not only wrote extensively about a Jewish return to Palestine but also boldly predicted the [building of the Third Temple](/Third_Temple) and foresaw [Jerusalem](/Jerusalem) assuming the most powerful role in global governance—all envisioned as preparatory steps for the [Second Coming](/Second_Coming). La Peyrère closely monitored the developments of Oliver Cromwell's Dissenter regime, even harboring dreams of overthrowing [Louis XIV of France](/Louis_XIV_of_France) and replacing him with the [Prince of Condé](/Louis,_Grand_Cond%C3%A9) (for whom he worked as a secretary) as part of a grand millennialist, proto-Zionist messianic project. Following the publication of La Peyrère's book, the Amsterdam-based Menasseh Ben Israel recognized the significance of these theories and brought them to the attention of his friend, [Petrus Serrarius](/Petrus_Serrarius), a close associate of John Dury. This interaction highlights an early, intriguing interplay between 17th-century Jewish and Protestant proto-Zionism. Other Continental Protestant millennialists, including the Germans [Abraham von Franckenberg](/Abraham_von_Franckenberg) (a scholar of the [Kabbalah](/Kabbalah)) and Paul Felgenhauer, were equally captivated by La Peyrère's theories. Menasseh Ben Israel himself would later author *The Hope of Israel* in 1652, further cementing these ideas. Serrarius, for his part, became the primary supporter among Amsterdam's Protestants for the declaration that [Sabbatai Zevi](/Sabbatai_Zevi) was indeed the [Messiah](/Messiah), a claim propagated by [Nathan of Gaza](/Nathan_of_Gaza) (whose followers, the [Sabbateans](/Sabbateans), were based in the [Ottoman Empire](/Ottoman_Empire) but garnered significant support across the [Jewish diaspora](/Jewish_diaspora)).

Even though they were removed from power in England, the millennialist [Puritans who had migrated to New England](/Puritan_migration_to_New_England_(1620%E2%80%931640)) left a lasting cultural legacy on society. Beyond John Cotton, [Increase Mather](/Increase_Mather), one of the early Presidents of [Harvard College](/Harvard_University), was a fervent advocate for the restoration of the Jews to Palestine. A prolific author, his most notable contribution in this regard was *The Mystery of Israel's Salvation* (1669). [Roger Williams](/Roger_Williams), the Puritan champion of [religious liberty](/Religious_liberty) (a concept so radical it even extended to Jews) in the [Colony of Rhode Island](/Colony_of_Rhode_Island_and_Providence_Plantations), which he founded, has been posthumously hailed as a proto-Zionist by later Jewish Zionist leaders like [Stephen S. Wise](/Stephen_S._Wise). This attribution stems from his profound comment, "I have longed after some trading with the Jews themselves, for whose hard measure I fear the nations and England have yet a score to pay." Some influential [17th-century philosophers](/17th-century_philosophy), who effectively bridged the gap between the millennialist sectarians of their era and the burgeoning [Age of the Enlightenment](/Age_of_the_Enlightenment) with its [Scientific Revolution](/Scientific_Revolution), either held views consistent with premillennial restorationists or moved closely within their circles. This is particularly true for Sir [Isaac Newton](/Isaac_Newton) and [Baruch Spinoza](/Baruch_Spinoza). Newton, especially, harbored [Radical Reformation](/Radical_Reformation) views [in terms of religion](/Religious_views_of_Isaac_Newton) and also notoriously [dabbled in the occult](/Isaac_Newton%27s_occult_studies), including the Kabbalah. He meticulously predicted a Jewish return to Palestine, complete with the rebuilding of Jerusalem in the late 19th century and the erection of the Third Temple in the 20th or 21st century, all culminating in the end of the world no later than 2060. Much of these private writings proved rather inconvenient and embarrassing for his supporters, who were keen to uphold him as a paragon of reason and science against the likes of [Leibniz](/Gottfried_Wilhelm_Leibniz). Consequently, while the [University of Cambridge](/University_of_Cambridge) eagerly inherited his scientific papers, they conspicuously declined to accept these more esoteric private ones. Many of these, later collected by [Abraham Yahuda](/Abraham_Yahuda), now reside in the [National Library of Israel](/National_Library_of_Israel) since 1967, a somewhat ironic final resting place. Spinoza, though Jewish himself, moved in intellectual circles in the Netherlands that included Petrus Serrarius and [Henry Oldenburg](/Henry_Oldenburg), and was even directly influenced by La Peyrère, demonstrating the interconnectedness of these early intellectual currents.

#### Pietism, Evangelicalism, and British foreign policy

•
See also: [Pietism](/Pietism), [Evangelicalism](/Evangelicalism), and [Political Zionism](/Political_Zionism)

•

